\section{Discussion and Experimental Signatures}

\subsection{Gravitational Wave Dispersion}
If the graviton (and spacetime itself) has a mass $m_\Phi$, gravitational waves will follow a modified dispersion relation:
\begin{equation}
E^2 = p^2 c^2 + m_\Phi^2 c^4
\end{equation}
This implies that lower-frequency gravitational waves travel slightly slower than $c$. While current LIGO constraints are tight ($m_g < 10^{-22}$ eV) \cite{abbott2016}, the \Es\ framework suggests this mass might be scale-dependent due to the non-linear screening mechanisms.

\subsection{Numerical Analysis of GW Dispersion}

To quantify the observable signatures, we performed numerical simulations of gravitational wave propagation with the massive dispersion relation:
\begin{equation}
v_g(f) = c \sqrt{1 - \left(\frac{m_g c^2}{h f}\right)^2} \approx c \left[1 - \frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{m_g c^2}{h f}\right)^2\right]
\end{equation}

The time delay between a massive and massless graviton signal from a source at distance $D$ is:
\begin{equation}
\Delta t \approx \frac{D}{2c} \left(\frac{m_g c^2}{h f}\right)^2
\end{equation}

Figure \ref{fig:gw_dispersion} shows the results for a source at $D = 400$ Mpc (typical binary merger distance). Key findings:

\begin{itemize}
    \item At the current LIGO limit ($m_g \sim 10^{-22}$ eV), the differential delay between 50 Hz and 200 Hz components is $\Delta t \approx 4.5$ ms.
    \item The fractional velocity reduction scales as $(c - v_g)/c \propto f^{-2}$, with lower frequencies more strongly affected.
    \item For $m_g = 10^{-21}$ eV (one order above LIGO limit), delays exceed 100 ms---easily detectable with current timing resolution.
\end{itemize}

